nglish, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mesle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Messler  .","Americanized form of German   Metzler  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Messler","meanings":["German: habitational name for someone from Messel near Darmstadt."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"L'Ainé","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maingot II L'Ainé de Mesle was born in 1025, in France, his father, Maingot I Er de Mesle, was 25 and his mother, Alaïdis e Mesle, was 20. He married Aïna Ou Lupa N about 1050, in France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1080, in Saint-Maixent-l'École, Deux-Sèvres, France, at the age of 55, and was buried in Saint-Maixent-l'École, Deux-Sèvres, France."},"et":{"1025–1080":"1025–1080","1060–1129":"1060–1129","1050–1098":"1050–1098","1000–1060":"1000–1060","1005–Female":"1005–Surnud","about 1050":"umbes 1050","1080":"1080","1129":"1129","1005":"1005","1025":"1025","1000":"1000","1098":"1098","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Saint Maixent, Deux Sevres, France":"Saint-Maixent-l'École, Deux-Sèvres, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1025–1080":"1025–1080","1060–1129":"1060–1129","1050–1098":"1050–1098","1000–1060":"1000–1060","1005–Female":"1005–Kuollut","about 1050":"noin 1050","1080":"1080","1129":"1129","1005":"1005","1025":"1025","1000":"1000","1098":"1098","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Saint Maixent, Deux Sevres, France":"Saint-Maixent-l'École, Deux-Sèvres, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"1025–1080":"1025–1080","1060–1129":"1060–1129","1050–1098":"1050–1098","1000–1060":"1000–1060","1005–Female":"1005–Décédée","about 1050":"environ 1050","1080":"1080","1129":"1129","1005":"1005","1025":"1025","1000":"1000","1098":"1098","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Saint Maixent, Deux Sevres, France":"Saint-Maixent-l'École, Deux-Sèvres, France","France":"France","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Maingot II L'Ainé de Mesle est né en 1025, à France, son père, Maingot I Er de Mesle, avait 25 ans et sa mère, Alaïdis